SIMPLE: grating
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grating
<hw>Grat"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[See 2d Grate.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A partition, covering, or frame of parallel or cross
bars; a latticework resembling a window grate; <as>as, the
<ex>grating</ex> of a prison or convent</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Optics)</fld> <def>A system of close equidistant
parallel lines or bars, esp. lines ruled on a polished surface, used for
producing spectra by diffraction; -- called also <altname>diffraction
grating</altname>.</def> <note>Gratings have been made with over 40,000
such lines to the inch, but those with a somewhat smaller number give
the best definition. They are used, e. g., to produce monochromatic
light for use in optical instruments such as
spectrophotometers.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>The strong
wooden lattice used to cover a hatch, admitting light and air; also, a
movable Lattice used for the flooring of boats.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grating</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grating
<hw>Grat"ing</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[See <er>Grate</er> to rub
harshy.]</ety> <def>That grates; making a harsh sound; harsh.</def> --
<wordforms><wf>Grat"ing*ly</wf>, adv.</wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grating</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grating
<hw>Grat"ing</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A harsh sound caused by
attrition.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gratiolin</ent>⟦br⟧
